   York, and sends them direct messages offering to promote them to
   followers in exchange for a comped meal â€” and no, it does not disclose
   that @beautiful.newyorkcity is run by a robot.

   Behold the latest chapter in the dark art of social media influencing,
   which despite being widely plagued with bots and fake engagement,
   continues to attract real interest from marketers and businesses.
   Buettiâ€™s account has (at least some) real followers, but the
   influencing itself is being handled by some code rather than an eager
   personality. Itâ€™s a lifestyle brand generated by something thatâ€™s not
   alive.

   Buetti isnâ€™t stopping at @beautiful.newyorkcity either. He also
   cofounded Social Rise Consulting, which uses similar tactics to grow
   clientsâ€™ followings online (for now, thatâ€™s namely mass following
   accounts to get follow backs). So far, Social Rise has 42 clients,
   according to its website. Itâ€™s all part of Buettiâ€™s portfolio of
   automation-related work; he considers the free food hustle a showcase
   for his talents as a data scientist, which he detailed in a Medium
   post. Buetti told BuzzFeed News so far @beautiful.newyorkcity has
   earned him about 10 free or discounted meals at some pretty nice
   restaurants.

   Does his scheme foreshadow a future in which influencing is automated?
   Buetti says thereâ€™s no reason influencing has to be personality driven
   â€” thereâ€™s another kind involving impersonal aggregators. â€œ@FuckJerry is
   where I got the idea,â€ he said, referencing the controversial meme
   kingpin. â€œHe never needs to show his face, he just posts memes he finds
   on the internet; mostly he just steals them.â€ He saw this as the
   perfect use case for automated posting: â€œI was thinking, this guy never
   needs to touch [by hand] his account ever.â€

